  "prompt": "What kind of economy does the United States have compared to the one in Guatemala?",
  "response": "The United States has a highly developed, diversified market economy characterized by advanced infrastructure, high technology, and a strong service sector. It is the world's largest economy with a GDP of over $22 trillion.\n\nIn contrast, Guatemala has a developing mixed economy that is much smaller, with an economy heavily dependent on agriculture, particularly coffee, sugar, and banana exports. Guatemala's GDP is significantly lower, around $76 billion, and it has higher levels of poverty and economic inequality compared to the United States.\n\nKey differences include:\n1. Economic complexity: US economy is much more complex and industrialized\n2. Per capita income: US has much higher average income\n3. Economic sectors: US has robust service and technology sectors, while Guatemala relies more on agriculture\n4. Infrastructure: US has more advanced infrastructure and technological development\n5. Economic stability: US economy is more stable and less vulnerable to external shocks\n\nWhile both are market economies, the United States has a much more developed and sophisticated economic system compared to Guatemala's emerging economy.",
